Something to that purpoſe are theſe French Verſes, made upon one by Monſieur de Furetiere;


Paul vend ſa Maiſon de S. Clou,

A maints Creanciers engagée.

Il dit par tout, qu'il en eſt ſoû;

Je le croi, car il l'a mangée.

Another French Poet of good Fame, being blamed for going always on foot, made theſe Extempore Verſes;




Je voi d'illuſtres Cavaliers,

Avec Laquais, Caroſſe, & Pages;

Mais ils doivent leurs Equipages,

Et je ne dois pas mes Souliers.

Another Poet made him this flattering Epitaph;


Rex HENRICUS obit, Deus olim, nunc Dolor Orbis;

Numina flent Numen deperiiſſe ſuum.

Mercurius minor Eloquio, vi Mentis Apollo,

Jupiter Imperio, Marſque Vigore gemunt, &c.

Queen JANE, who died in Child-birth of King Edward VI, and uſed for her Device a Phenix, being her paternal Creſt had this alluding thereunto for her Epitaph;


Phaenix Jana jacet, nato Phaenice, dolendum

Saecula Phaenices nulla tuliſſe duos.

The ſaid King EDWARD, being ſnatched away by Death in his Youth, had this Diſtich made upon him;


Rex, Regis Natus, Regum Decus, unica Regni

Speſque Saluſque ſui, conditur hoc Tumulo.

One without Name had this Inſcription on his Grave;


VIXI, PECC AVI, PAENITƲI,

NATƲRAE CESSI.

                  Diego de Valles made this Inſcription for his Tomb at Rome;


Certa Dies nulli eſt, Mors certa, incerta ſequentum

Cura; locet Tumulum qui ſapit ante ſibi.

                  Julius Scaliger, only this;
SCALIGERI QƲOD RELIQƲ
                     ƲM.

Upon Sir Philip Sidney, I find this;



                        England had his Body, for ſhe it fed;


                        Netherland his Blood, in her Defence ſhed;



The Heavens have his Soul,

the Arts have his Fame;

The Souldier the Grief,

the World his good Name.

Upon a Young Man of great hope, a Student of Oxford made this;


Short was thy Life,

Yet liveſt thou ever;

Death has her due,

Yet dieſt thou never.

Pleaſant was the Epitaph made upon an ignorant French Abbot, in theſe words;


Cy gît un ignorant Abbé,

Qui ne ſavoit ni A, ni B.

A drunken Man, Elderton by Name, had this made upon him;


Hîc ſitus eſt ſitiens, atque ebrius Eldertonus,


Quid dico, hîc ſitus eſt? hîc potiùs ſitis eſt.

Upon an old Miſer, Sparges by Name, this was made;


Here lieth Father Sparges,


That died to ſave Charges.

Upon a capricious Man, this;


Here lieth Willing Wills,

With his Head full of Wind-mills.

Upon another, who was ever out of humour;


Here lieth he,

Who with himſelf could never agree.

He was more happy in a Wife, who wrote this Diſtich upon her, after her Deceaſe;


Quae pia, quae prudens, quae provida, pulchra fuiſti,


                        Ʋxor in aeternum, Chara MARIA, vale.

Upon a Dier;


He that died ſo oft in ſport,

Died at laſt, no colour for't.

On a Gold-ſmith that Tipt Stone-Jugs with Silver;


He that did tip Stone-Jugs about the Brim,

Met with a black Pot, and the Pot tipt him.

Upon a Wreſtler;


Death to this Wreſtler gave a fine Fall,

That tript up his Heels, and took no hold at all.

On a Butcher that marry'd a Tanner's Daughter;


A fitter Match has never bin,

The Fleſh is marry'd to the Skin.

Upon two beautiful Children, Brother and Siſter, who wanted each of them an Eye;


Lumine Acon dextro caruit, Leonilla ſiniſtro,

Et potuit Formâ vincere uterque Deos.

Parve Puer, Lumen quod habes concede Sorori;

Sic tu caecus AMOR, ſic erit illa VENƲS.
